commentBody:
@Sam Lyons 

Beautiful first paragraph and nice use of PSI (loved the cluing for 1A). PSI with relief still has me chuckling!



.

@Sam Lyons

For me, it was getting PEEKABOO off the K and then BOHEMIAN RHAPSODY off the B. Fun.

(Hope you survived the cold! We were at our mountain cabin when it was 3 below—on the west side of Stevens Pass—and then the power went out. Fortunately, the wood stove chugged along, and after lighting some candles, the youngsters found out that the oldsters aren’t as lame as they thought at either blackjack or Monopoly.)

@john ezra 
Thanks, j.e. Sam Ezersky makes for the best muse. I do love his puzzles and, oh, what I wouldn’t give for another Saturday of his. 

@kkseattle
Freddie Mercury has ceded his place in my head to Dana Carvey and Mike Myers [toothy grin]. 

Blackjack by candlelight sounds fantastic… Hope you got some good skiing in, too. We stayed at our Sammamish place through the cold week. There was no way I was walking The Dog in that weather if we’d stayed in Seattle — both she and I are still high desert girls at heart. I stuck my nose outside maybe once, only to shut the door very quickly again. All the rain out here is wonderful, it really is, but y’all can keep it when it freezes…

@Jannicut 

Yes to all your points, even as my quibble with those who use HERSTORY in earnest is always first and foremost etymological. 

Having said that, after my initial flinch at seeing the entry, it occurred to me that crossword puzzle grids don’t account for spaces between phrases: Sam Ezersky just as likely had meant HER STORY, and the fact that it could also be read as HERSTORY would have just added to his sense of wordplay.

@Kris T 

Thank you for the compliment.

If you were also answering my question, I was referring to a themer I threw into the story (phonetically not symbolically).

@Eric Hougland 

Thanks. I’ve thought about doing it. I just don’t like the idea of them having my NYT login. 

But I often quote their stats for providing ‘evidence’ that a particular puzzle was “easy  or hard”. But man. Those that use that service are speedsters. The averages are humbling ; for me)

@Keith 
Many humans have uttered it. "Attaboy" or "attagirl" is more common, but when the subject is non-gendered or plural, you use ATTAWAY. 

I have discovered that it's best not to use one's own experience to define the world. Something I've never heard of may be commonly known in other parts. :)

@drsophila 

The American Psychological Assn uses PSI as its symbol (isn't that cute?) and I married a 'social psychologist' who consulted with businesses and organizations.  

Given the recent appearances of PSI and ATTA WAY, you can see that we were being primed (or 'softened up') for the next exposure ....and "Unlikely Plurals for $600, Alex" for ARSONS....

